   412→                           It is easy to see that almost all numbers are not practical. Erdős originally showed that $h(n!) &lt;n$. Vose <a href="#cite-Vo85-18" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Vo85','18'); return false;">[Vo85]</a> proved the existence of infinitely many practical $m$ such that $h(m)\ll (\log m)^{1/2}$. <br><br>The sequence of practical numbers is <a href="https://oeis.org/A005153" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">A005153</a> in the OEIS.<br><br>The reward of \$250 is offered in <a href="#cite-Er81h-18" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er81h','18'); return false;">[Er81h]</a>, apparently (although this is not entirely clear) for a proof or disproof of whether\[h(n!) &lt;(\log n)^{O(1)}.\]See also <a href="/304" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[304]</a> and <a href="/825" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[825]</a>.
